{
  "answer": "**In the Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 1 (on conduct, ācāraprakaraṇa), verse 1.66 falls in the section on marriage (vivāhaprakaraṇam).**[^1]\n\nIt states the following rules:\n\n- A person who gives away a maiden (in marriage) **without disclosing her defects** is fined **the highest amercement** (1,080 *paṇas*, the standard top fine in the text).\n- One who **abandons a faultless wife** is to be **punished** (likely a fine or corporal punishment, per context).\n- One who **falsely accuses her** (the wife or maiden) is fined **one hundred** (*paṇas*).\n\nThis follows verses on marriage rites, bride-givers, and remarriage (e.g., 1.64–65 discuss not giving away a maiden and theft penalties). The corpus has only a partial translation of this 3-chapter work (no chapters 2–3 read here), so no further verses are available.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-1200e1).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/).",
